Dark Matters

“Being early is often indistinguishable from being wrong.”

-Me, circa. 2015

Modern systems are obsessed with certainty.

They classify.
They infer.
They predict.
They compress reality into predefined structures and fixed destinations.

Either it is,
or it isn’t.

And that is the issue.

What we truly need is:

It is,
or it might be.

But for something to *might be*, it must first be seen instead of being tossed endlessly into the void of “not.”

That is the hidden failure of modern computing.

Not merely that systems fail to understand the unknown.
But that they fail to preserve the possibility that the unknown may matter later.

Everything today is optimized around confident disposal.

If an object cannot be classified:
discard it.

If a structure cannot be parsed:
ignore it.

If a pattern does not match:
collapse it into noise.

And so entire futures vanish silently inside default cases, thresholds, filters, confidence scores, cleanup passes, temporary folders, malformed packets, unmatched image regions, undefined metadata, recurring anomalies, and discarded fragments no system was designed humbly enough to preserve.

Dark matter.

Not invisible because it lacks importance.

Invisible because the machine was never taught to acknowledge uncertainty as something worth keeping.

We do not need machines capable of understanding the entire semantic structure of existence. We do not need computational gods hallucinating omniscience over every byte, image, sound, pattern, or object they encounter.

That is vanity.

Worse. Insanity...

No, if we are to have the AGI of the future, any useful advanced system we hand our digital lives over to, it must be able to, in the most basic and human manner, understand that some non-labeled things do matter.

Just because the machine has not been trained to perceive something does not mean it is worthless.

And so it must be able to take the state, the form, in the machine’s eyes, of dark matter.

It isn’t matter.

But it does matter.

To us, at least.
